                    PART 2 THE SCRIBBLE! OVERVIEW
                             INTRODUCTION

   Welcome to the SCRIBBLE! Overview. In this section of the manual,
we are going to cover material about the program in a topical manner.
If you're looking for a command-by-command breakdown of the program,
that's contained in the SCRIBBLE! Reference Guide (part 3 of the
manual). Someone who has not used a word processor before today should
probably make certain they have gone through the SCRIBBLE Tutorial
before beginning here. The Tutorial will acquaint you with the basics
or writing with a word processor.

   SCRIBBLE! is a powerful full featured word processing program that
will help you produce beautifully formatted reports and documents. You
can use SCRIBBLE! to write memos, letters, reports or as an adjunct to
OnLine! (our popular Amiga terminal program) to create script files.

   A word processor is not just a fancy electric typewriter. The real
value of a word processor is in the two step process between creating
(typing) the document and storing it on electronic media (disks) and
the completion (printing) of the document. Because the document is not
printed as you type it, you have the opportunity to edit and revise it
before putting it on paper.

2-1
   With a typewriter, you are forced to re-type the entire document or
at least the page. The word processor's electronic file can be easily
edited with just a few keystrokes. The printer can then print out the
corrected version in a matter of minutes, no longer demanding the
writer's attention.

TWO STEPS TO A FINISHED DOCUMENT

   *Writing. Documents are created using SCRIBBLE! and your computer.
As each key is pressed, the character is displayed on the screen and
stored in your computer's memory. When you have completed typing your
document, the contents of memory (which is temporary storage) can be
stored on disk (for more permanent storage and later recall).

   *Printing. Printing is a separate process that involves taking your
document and sending it to the printer according to formatting
instructions that control margins, line spacing, pagination, special
printing features, underlines, etc. The final printed document may
look very different from the original version displayed on your
screen. As a matter of face, a single document can be generate a wide
range of printed documents depending upon the formatting and printing
instructions used.

2-2
WRITING A DOCUMENT

   Before you can write a document, you must start up the program. To
do this, either select the SCRIBBLE! icon from the Workbench screen or
type "SCRIBBLE!" at the CLI prompt and press RETURN. (If you're
running the program from CLI, make sure that your current directory is
the one which contains the SCRIBBLE! program file.)

   In either case, the disk drive will activate for a few moments
while the program loads. When SCRIBBLE has been loaded, a large blank
window appears wit  a cursor in the upper left hand corner. At the
bottom of the screen is a second window that functions as a status box
to show you the location of the cursor, various edit modes, and other
indicators.  You can begin typing.

