PRINTING A DOCUMENT

   Before you can print a document with SCRIBBLE!, you need to use the
Preferences tool supplied by AmigaDOS to configure for your printer.
If you are not sure how to use Preferences, consult your Amiga user's
manual for details.

   A portion of the Preferences printer configuration allows you to
set margins for your printer. To work with SCRIBBLE!, you need to set
the the left margin to 1 and the right margin to 255. In this manner,
you assure that Preferences will not start wrapping lines (reserving
this for SCRIBBLE!).

   Once you have used Preferences to set up for your printer, you are
ready to print out a document. Obviously, you must first either load
some text from a disk file or type some in from the edit mode. When
the text is in the window and you're ready to print,

2-8
select the Printer subcommand of the Go command on the Print menu
(i.e., Print Go Printer). Your printout will begin immediately. NOTE:
What you do when you printer is not on the list supported by
Preference? At the end of this overview section, there is information
for advanced uses of SCRIBBLE!. We'll cover this in there.

ARCHIVING DOCUMENT FILES

   In order to store documents for future reference, you need to store
them on disk. How do you do this? Well, first you should select the
Archive Documents command of the Project menu. When the Archive
Requester appears, it will be displaying all of the files in the
currently logged directory. If this is not the drive you wish to store
the file on, select the Dir icon and enter the new drive and/or
directory name. (for example, if DF0: was the currently logged
directory, and you wanted to store the file in a directory on drive 1
called DOC-FILES, you would select the Dir icon and enter ("DF:1DOC-
FILES") when the requester appeared).

   Once you have the correct drive and/or directory selected, all you
need to do is select the Store icon. Enter the name of the file you
are saving. Since you chose Archive Documents instead of Archive
Document,

2-9
SCRIBBLE! will add the pattern ".doc" to the end of the filename for
us. Archive Documents also displays only those files with the ".doc"
pattern in them. This is a convenient way to keep your document files
segregated on a crowded disk.

ARCHIVING NON-DOCUMENT FILES

   If you use SCRIBBLE! to write a Script (.scp) file or other non-
document file for an application using a specific pattern in its
files, you'll need to use the Archive General command, instead of the
Archive Document command, and specify the pattern yourself, otherwise
the other application program may not be able to locate it.

   For example, if you write a script file for OnLine!, you would
select Archive General, make sure that you had specified the correct
drive and directory, and then select Store. When SCRIBBLE! prompted
you for a filename, you'd enter the filename with a ".scp" pattern at
the end (i.e., RBBS,scp).

