2-12
LEAVING SCRIBBLE! (QUIT)

   Leaving SCRIBBLE! is a two-step process. First, you must either
select the Quit command on the Project menu or type Amiga-Q. This
action will bring up a requester asking you to make SURE you want to
Quit. If you have saved any document currently in memory, you may
select Yes and exit SCRIBBLE!.

   CHANGING YOUR DEFAULT VALUES

   SCRIBBLE! lets you reprogram certain default characteristics such
as line length, ink and paper colors, justification, and margins.
These are all accomplished with the Default menu.

   The first option on this menu is Archive. This works in a similar
manner to Project Archive, except that it is loading and saving
"format files" instead of documents. These format files, which have
".fmt" at the end of their filenames, will remember each and every
setting you have specified with the Default menu commands. Later, you
can reload one of these files to instantly reconfigure SCRIBBLE!.

   SCRIBBLE will look for the file SCRIBBLE!.fmt in the current
directory when it powers up. If it is there, the values contained in
it will be loaded and used. It does not HAVE to be present. SCRIBBLE!
does have your favorite configuration as the new default.

2-13
TEXT JUSTIFICATION

   This can be controlled two ways. First, there is a command on the
Default menu which can engage right hand margin justification (both
margin smooth). This will also turn on justification for the display.
The program will add "soft spaces" on the screen to fill out each line
until the margins are smooth.

   To see these spaces, you can turn on the special "background"
display by typing Shift-F10. This shows all the spaces on the screen
that you did not type with the space bar as a reverse video "hash".
You can use this to see how many spaces are really at the end of a
line, or to see the soft spaces inserted into a line when
justification is on.

   This can be very useful when editing those lines. You see, if you
should happen to overtype a soft space with a regular one, SCRIBBLE!
can no longer add and subtract it as needed to keep the line smooth.
It will stay there permanently. By turning on the background you can
see the soft spaces and steer clear of them. In addition, there is a
command to temporarily remove the soft space from a line while you're
editing it. Typing ALT-R will make the soft space disappear until you
move the cursor off the line.

   In addition to the Default Justify menu command, there are a
sequence of dot commands that can be used in format lines to further
control text justification.

2-14
   A complete list of dot commands appears later in this section, but
the justification commands are:

     JU   Justification on or off.  This is a duplicate of the
          Default Justify menu command, and will override the
          current status of the command (i.e. you can have
          justification on the screen, and edit the document
          that way, but if you have a ".JU=N" command on a
          format line in the document, there will be no
          justification).

     FR   Engages "flush right" justification, in which text is
          printed smooth to the right hand margin, but ragged to
          the left. This is used when you want to set some text
          against the right hand margin (e.g. a date in a letter,
          or some numbers in columns.

     HI   Hanging indent. This command sets a column position
          where the text should begin when the PROGRAM wraps a
          line. If the line is ended manually, this does not
          take effect. Only when a line is wrapped by the program
          will this indent be used. This is useful in creating
          "bullet" paragraphs.

   The first two of the dot commands listed above are either on or
off. The parameters they accept are "Y" and "N" (e.g. JU=Y or FR=N).
The third is a column position, and as such is specified with a
numeric value (HI=10).

2-15
LINE LENGTH AND HORIZONTAL SCROLLING

   A full size SCRIBBLE edit window can display 76 characters on a
line. We make the distinction of "full sized" because you can use the
sizing gadget to shrink a window (as in the case of multiple windows
visible at the same time).

   Should your line length be greater than the number of characters
that will fit on the screen SCRIBBLE! will not be able to show you all
of the characters on the line at one time.  In these cases, horizontal
scrolling will automatically take place. Also, the proportional scroll
gadget at the bottom of the edit window can be used in displaying the
text not visible on the line.

   If your line length is LESS than the number of characters SCRIBBLE!
can display on a line, the program will automatically center your text
in the window. This does not mean that the extra margins will print on
the page. It is merely visual aesthetics.

   Line length can be adjusted from within your document with the LL
(Line Length) dot command (e.g. LL=55). This is useful when you need
to temporarily shorten the line length, as with an inset paragraph, or
when you want to edit the document with a line length OTHER than the
one you wish to print with. However, to have your line breaks
displayed properly, you should set the display line length to the same
value as your printed line length.

2-16
SETTING TABS:

   SCRIBBLE! features user definable tab positions. Even though these
do not show of the screen, you can still adjust them. If you use the
Default Tabs command, SCRIBBLE! will prompt you for a list of column
positions for the tab stops. For specific details look up this command
in the Reference Guide.

   Tab stops will be saved in the format files, so you should only
have to enter them once.

DISPLAY COLORS

   SCRIBBLE! is a Workbench compatible application, and as such uses
the four display colors defined for your copy of Workbench by
Preferences. However, you can decide what combination of colors to use
for the text (Ink) and background (Paper).

   As you change the colors with Preferences, the colors within
SCRIBBLE! will also change. The current color settings will be saved
in your format files.

   Many people find that changing colors in each window makes working
with multiple windows much more convenient and less mistake prone.

SETTING UP THE DEFAULT PAGE SIZE

   There are several commands on the Default menu that are used in
defining the default page size. One of

2-17
these is Line Length, which has already been covered. The others are
contained as sub-options under the Print command of the Default menu.

   The Page Length option lets you tell SCRIBBLE! how many lines long
each page should be. The default value is 66, which is standard for an
11 inch page with a line spacing of 6 lines per inch. Unless you are
printing on some other size paper, or with some other line spacing,
you should not change this value.

   The Page Offset value tells SCRIBBLE! how many spaces to print at
the start of each line when it's printing out your document. This will
not show on the screen, since it is only of value when printing out
hardcopy. In some applications, you many want to indent more on one
page than the next (the logical application here is printing text that
will be copied on two sided paper). To help with this, you can use the
dot commands EO (Even Offset) and OO (Odd Offset) to set a separate
page offset for even and odd numbered pages.

   The other two options of the Default Print command that affect page
layout are Top Margin and Bottom Margin. This are the number of lines
SCRIBBLE! will skip at the top and bottom of each page. This is used
to prevent the program from printing on the perforation of fanfold
paper or skip down over letterhead. The number of lines actually
USABLE on a page can be calculated by subtracting the top and bottom
margins from the Page Length.

2-18
   Once you have told SCRIBBLE! how long the page is, how long your
lines are, and how many lines you will be skipping for top and bottom
margins, it has a pretty clear picture of how big your page is. It
will use this in calculating the "current page" number that is shown
in the status window. If you use dot commands in your text that can
alter the page breaks at print time (HI - Hanging Indent, and CP -
Conditional Page are two good examples), the current page indicator
may not be accurate. In those cases, use the ALT-J command to jump to
the next printed page break.

  You can also define a setup string that will be sent to the printer
before any text. Remember that if you are using the normal SCRIBBLE!
printer routines, this will be sent via the Preferences printer drive,
so this setup code should be something that IT will understand. If you
are using the "print to file" function and printing directly to the
parallel port (i.e. printing to PAR:), then the string and all other
data will be sent to the printer untranslated.

CARRIAGE RETURNS, LINE FEEDS, AND OTHER FORMATS

   SCRIBBLE! places a paragraph symbol in the text wherever you press
RETURN. You can decide what this paragraph symbol will be when the
file is stored to disk. You may choose between a carriage return, a
line feed, or a carriage returned followed by a line feed.

2-19
   Standard Amiga text file format is a line feed, and this is the
power up default. However, a file that will be uploaded to a bulletin
board or information network will likely need a carriage return
followed by a line feed.

   When SCRIBBLE! loads a file, it looks at the text to see what
format was used when the file was stored on the disk. It then moves
the check mark for you, so that you can load, edit, and save a
document without changing the format and without altering it.

   If you WANT to alter the format of a document, just use the Default
Format command and move the check mark to a new location.

   You'll probably want to store your most commonly used format as
part of your default format file.

CHANGING WORDS AND PHRASES THROUGHOUT A DOCUMENT

   After writing a memo or report, you may have the misfortune of
finding out that Mr. "Smith" spells his name "S-M-I-T-H-E". With a
word processor, the change is easy, involving only two steps.

   First tell SCRIBBLE! what to search for. Select the Search command
on the Text menu. You will be asked to enter the character string to
find. Enter

2-20
"Smith". Immediately the cursor moves to the first location of Smith.
If all you want to do is "find" the various locations of Smith, you
can repeat the process by clicking the left mouse button or pressing
the F9 function key.

   To "change" the various occurrences of Smith to Smithe, go back and
select the Replace command on the Text menu. SCRIBBLE! asks you to
enter the change string (what you want the string to have found
earlier to be changed into). Enter "Smithe".

   SCRIBBLE! will search out every occurrence of Smith and prompt to
see if you want to change it into Smithe. Note the Search and Replace
commands are case dependent. If you instruct SCRIBBLE! to search for
"this", it will not find "This".

   Also note that a Search and/or Replace operation advance from the
top of the document down each time you run it. If you are planning on
searching for a string skipping the first few occurrences, and then
starting to replace it, you should define the Search string and then
immediately go into the Replace mode and use the Next option to skip.

   All you need do now is click the left mouse button or press the F9
function key to replace the "next" occurrence, which will be the
string you are currently positioned over.

2-21
USES FOR SEARCH AND REPLACE

   The Search command can be used in a mail list or catalog (if you
have typed in all of the information as a document file) to locate
individual records and files. For example, you could look for a
particular zip code in a mailing list, or a phone number, occupation,
etc. Unlike a file management program, there is no need to design a
special file. Just select Search and enter the string of characters
you are searching for.

   Remember that SCRIBBLE! is literal and case dependent. Make sure
that you have spelled the string properly and capitalized it just the
way it appears in the document. (Sometimes, if you are searching for a
word that may or may not be capitalized, you can omit the first
character. For example, search for "eturn" to find "return" and
"Return".)

BLOCK OPERATIONS: CUT, COPY, PASTE

   Performing a block operation in SCRIBBLE! is simple. First you tell
the program what sort of operation you would like to perform, and when
you tell it what text to perform the operation upon.

   There are three block operation commands on the Text menu. Cut is
used to delete text from one location and, if you wish, insert it at
another (with Paste). Copy is used to duplicate text from one

2-22
location in the document to another. And Paste is used to insert text
that has been cut or copied.

   When you select the type operation that you want your mouse pointer
will change shape and the "Action" indicator in the status window will
reflect the new mode. SCRIBBLE! will remain in this mode until
specifically told to return to the Edit mode.

   Once in the proper mode, it is a simple matter to define the text
you wish to operate upon. There are two methods, one using the mouse
and the other using the keyboard. You MUST use the keyboard method if
the text you wish to define is not completely displayed on the screen
at one time. If you can see all of the text you wish to operate on,
you can use the mouse.

   To define a block of text with the mouse, point at the start of the
block, press and hold the left mouse button, point at the end of the
block (which causes the text to highlight as you move), and release
the left mouse button. The block operation correct for the currently
engaged mode (Cut or Copy) will be performed as soon as you release
the mouse button.

   If you make a mistake when defining the block with the mouse and
you want to get out of the block definition sequence, just move the
mouse pointer off the edit window on the left hand or top borders. The
block definition will be instantly aborted and you can release the
left mouse button.

2-23
   Defining a block of text with the keyboard is equally simple. Move
the cursor to where you want the block to begin and press the F9
function key. Move the cursor to the end of the block, which will
cause the text to highlight as you move, and press RETURN. The
indicated block operation will be instantly performed.

   To delete a block of text, simply cut it and forget about it. If
you want to move the block, first you must cut it, and then select the
Paste mode. When you're in the paste mode either move the cursor to
where you want the block to be and press F9 or point with the mouse
(if you're moving it to a location on the screen currently) and click
the left button.

   Copying a block is identical, except that you must use the Copy
command instead of Cut. Copy just "takes a picture" of the text (which
is the reason for the mouse pointer taking on a camera shape). Then
when you use Paste and insert it somewhere else in the document,
you'll have two copies of the block.

   The block operation even work between windows. This is how you
would append two documents, for example. Load the first document into
window one, open a second window and load the second document into it.
Then either Cut or Copy the document in the second window and Paste it
into the first (or vice versa, depending on what you want to end up
with).

2-24
STYLING YOUR TEXT

   The same general rules apply when styling existing text. As you saw
in the list command keys covered earlier, you can change the style of
your text while you are typing it in by using the special function
keys assigned to this task. However, applying style to existing text
is another matter altogether.

   First, just as with block operations, you must define the style you
wish to apply. Select the Style command on the Text menu and a pop-out
menu appears with your choices listed on it. You may choose either
Plain or any combination of the other three. (This does mean that
Plain overrides the other settings.)

   Once you've defined what style to apply, the mouse pointer will
assume the shape of an artist's paint brush and the "Action" indicator
in the status window will read "Style". Now, just define the block you
want to style exactly as described above for the other block
operations.

   To remove all style from text that is already styled, you only need
to apply the Plain "style" to it. Plain is actually the absence of
other styles.

2-26
THE EDITOR'S TOOL BOX

   No word processor would be worth the disk it's stored on if it did
not include a host of text manipulation functions to make the job of
editing a document simpler.

   SCRIBBLE! offers you the ability to move, copy and delete marked
blocks of text. You can move quickly through a document, deleting and
inserting characters. Special printing functions like boldface and
underline are available, along with other advanced formatting
features.

   While many SCRIBBLE! functions utilize easy to operate menus, a
good number are also activated by keyboard commands. The flow of work
is made faster and more efficient by speeding the development of text
without distracting the user's attention to a menu. A number of
"transparent" commands are used for simple operations. They are
sometimes called "ALT commands", since they are activated by pressing
the ALT key, and while continuing to hold the ALT key, pressing one
additional key.

   Some commands use the "Amiga key" sequence, instead. This entails
pressing and holding the right hand Amiga key (the stylized A) and
typing the proper letter. Amiga keys are sued when the command is a
duplicate of a command found in the menu structure (such as Copy and
Paste). SCRIBBLE! provides these for many command menu commands.

2-26
