     ALT D  Delete character under cursor
         E  Cursor to last line of document, but same column
         G  Imbed Printer control code
         I  Toggle the Insert/Overwrite modes of text entry
         J  Moves cursor to next (printed) page break
         L  Deletes the current line (permanently)
         P  Force new page
         Q  Quit changes to line
         R  Temporarily remove justified spaces from a line to
            allow better editing
         S  Delete all spaces up to the next non-space character
         T  Cursor to first line of document, but same column

2-27
PRINTING OUT YOUR DOCUMENTS AND FORMAT LINES

   If you wish to change the margins, spacing or other printer
characteristics temporarily, you can enter a format line into the body
of the text. A format line is any line which begins with a period
character. SCRIBBLE! will not print any of text on this line, but
rather scans the line for legal dot commands. A dot command is a two
letter command, an equals mark, and an argument (sometimes a value,
sometimes a Y/N switch). For example, to set a temporary left margin,
change the line length and active justification (which is something
you might do for an insert paragraph), you'd use the format line:

   .LM=10,LL=40,JU=Y

   Note that all three commands can be on the same line as long as
they are separated by commas.

   Remember that if this a temporary format, you must re-set to the
original specifications after the affected block. For example, you
might return to a format something like:

   .LM-0,LL=54,JU=N

   Dot commands will not alter the way the text looks on the display
screen. Only menu commands can do that. Dot commands will only be seen
when your text is actually printing (or when you use Print Preview).

2-28
IMBEDDING SPECIAL PRINTER CONTROL COMMANDS

   You can insert control characters to activate special print
characteristics that may be supported by your printer. Use the
following format:

  .#O/x=string of characters

   The "#O" tells SCRIBBLE! to use this code when it sees the ALT-G
symbol followed by a "O". The "x" is either O or 1 (1 means that the
string will produce a printed character, so justify it; O means that
the string is for printer control only). The string of characters can
be either (ASCH text or control characters (e.g. "A would send a CTRL-
A). Also allowed are decimal values, preceded by a percent sign (e.g,
%221 would send a 221 decimal). When reading decimal numbers, input
will be accepted until the next non-numeric digit (or for a maximum of
three digits, whichever happens first).

   Any ASCH character can be "programmed" into a document with this
feature following the insertion of the proper format line such as this
example.

   .#O/1=%175

   The "." tell SCRIBBLE! that a format line is coming. The #O tells
it that we are defining a code that will follow ALT-G, in this case
the numeral "O" (although it could be any between O and 9). The "/1"
tells you

2-29
that the 175 character will be a printable character; if you wish to
specify a non-printable control sequence such as superscript or
subscript, it should be followed by a "/O", that way it will not alter
text justification. The "%175" is the decimal equivalent of a
paragraph symbol on some printers. (Consult your printer manual for a
listing of characters and their decimal equivalents).

   Most printer manuals list the special characters on a reference
page. Usually each character is listed with its decimal, hexadecimal,
octal and sometimes binary code. SCRIBBLE! uses only the decimal
value.

   So in addition to the normal boldface, underline, and italic codes,
you can "program" ten more to be used at your discretion.

   If you are using a printer driver specified with the Preferences
tool, then you'll want to specify escape sequences that it understands
with these printer variables. (In other words, if you want to
superscript on your printer, instead of sending the code that makes
your printer superscript, send the code that makes Preferences
superscript on your printer.)

