HEADER AND FOOTER FORMATS

   No word processor is complete without Headers (titles at the top of
the page) and Footers (titles at the bottom). SCRIBBLE! supports both.
Although it only allows a single line for a title, the format within
this line is most flexible with several built in convenience
functions.

   The symbol @ and # can be used to include the current date @ or
page number (#) within a title. When the @ symbol appears the result
is the date printed in the following format: DD-MON-YY.

   Here's a list of all the title commands (a title is a header or
footer), and some examples of how they work and what sort of output
they generate:

TITLE FORMAT
COMMAND             PRINT LOCATION

.HE Header          Top Margin
.FO Footer          Bottom Margin
.EH Even Header     Even Pages (Top Margin)
.OH Odd Header      Odd Pages (Top Margin)
.EF Even Footer     Even Page (Bottom Margin)
.OF Odd Footer      Odd Page (Bottom Margin)

2-37
   All these titles follow the same general format:

     .HE=Left/Center/Right

   Examples:

     .HE=@/Page #/SCRIBBLE!

   Header Results:

     11-MAY-86         Page 1          SCRIBBLE!

     .HE=//SCRIBBLE!

   Header Result:

                                        SCRIBBLE!

   Header Result:

   SCRIBBLE!

   .HE=/Page #/

   Header Result:

Page 1
2-38
   Footers work just like headers, except using ".FO" instead of
".HE". Also, if you boldface or underline part of the header/footer
text, then that portion of the header or footer will be boldfaced or
underlined when printed out.  However, take care not to apply any
special style to the format dot commands themselves. SCRIBBLE! will
not understand a boldfaced ".HE".

   SPECIAL PAGE CONTROL

     .SS=Y/N        Single Sheet paper used
     .HM=xx         Header Margin (xx lines)
     .FM=xx         Footer Margin (xx lines)
     .PL=xx         Physical Page Length (default 66)
     .PS=xx         Page spacing between pages (MB + MT)
     .MT=xx         Margin Top (default 6)
     .MB=xx         Margin Bottom (default 6)
     .CP=xx         Conditional Page (new page; <xx lines)

   Page Spacing (PS) is a combination of Margin Top and Margin Bottom.
Some people prefer to think in terms of Page Length (PL) - Page
Spacing (PS) = usable lines. If you choose to use this parameter, your
top margin will be set to 0 and the bottom margin to whatever value PS
is equal to.

   Conditional Page (CP) lets you tell SCRIBBLE! how many lines MUST
fit on the button of a page before it may start a paragraph on that
page. If, for example, CP is equal to "5", then SCRIBBLE! will check
to make sure that it can print at least 5 lines of each paragraph
before starting it on that page.

2-39
   Keep in mind that lines where you have manually pressed RETURN
(such as tables and columnar data), will be considered as separate
paragraphs. Sometimes this causes confusing results. This anti-orphan
feature is one of the dot commands that will cause the active page
indicator in the status window to be inaccurate. If you're using this
command, you may have to use ALT-J to correctly display your page
breaks.

